722407f-a.title: Manhattan: Park Avenue - 132nd Street
722407f-a.text:
Park Ave., west side, north from, and including East 132nd Street, show-
ing (extreme right), a portion of the N.Y. Central R.R. elevated structure,
which, at this point, mmakes a sharp bend eastward, and heads across the Harlem
yiver.
December 16, 1936.
P. L. Sperr.
NO REPRODUCTIONS.

722408f-a.title: Manhattan: Park Avenue - 132nd Street (East)
722408f-a.text:
Park Ave., west side, north from East 132nd to 135th Streets,
showing same in a panoramio arrangement of 2 views. In the foreground is
a clearance that incorporates that block front between 132nd and 133rd
Streets. Across same appear structures facing on West 133rd Street;
those of which the rears appear bear Nos. 60 to 50 inclusive, while
those on the opposite side bear Nos. 55, 6l, 53 and 65. The latter
structure is also known as 1980 Park Ave. On the extreme right are the
Central Coal Yards at the foot of East 135th Street and on west bank
of the Harlem River.
April 16, 1937.
P. L. Sperr.
NO REPRODUCTIONS.

722409f-a.title: Manhattan: Park Avenue - 132nd Street
722409f-a.text:
The same, showing a view farther south. The S.W. corner of East 133rd
Street is now an empty lot as a result of the demolition of three houses
which formerly occupied this site (see view 1). Also note the empty space
(in centre of view) caused by the demolition of one of the houses. Also
visible (on extreme left) is a portion of the elevated structure of the
New York Central Railroad which, at this point, makes a sharp bend eastward
and heads across the Harlem River.
December 16, 1936.
P. L. Sperr.
NO REPRODUCTIONS.
(3)
The same, from a point slightly northward. The prominent 5-story building
shown is No. 1950 Park Ave., at the N.W. corner of East 133rd Street and
also bears No. 65 East 133rd Street. Also seen (in centre of view) are the
rears of 3-story houses facing on the north side of East 132nd Street.
December 16, 1936.
P.  'L. Sperr.
NO REPRODUCTIONS.
